{# ══ Activity 1 — Introduction ═══════════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(1, "Introduction to the Clarity Filter", "eye") %}
<p>
  Errors in clarity affect the reader's understanding of the meaning. The meaning
  may be lost completely, or the reader may not be able to understand exactly what
  you mean. Errors of clarity are due to <strong>vague</strong> or
  <strong>ambiguous</strong> language usage.
</p>
<p>When checking your draft using the clarity filter, there are five error types to look out for:</p>
<ol>
  <li>Use of vague expressions</li>
  <li>Lexical ambiguity</li>
  <li>Referential ambiguity</li>
  <li>Syntactic ambiguity</li>
  <li>Garden-path sentences</li>
</ol>

{{ videoEmbed("oPDh0TQ0GB8", "Introduction to the clarity filter") }}
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 2 — Vague expressions ══════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(2, "Use of Vague Expressions", "question-circle") %}
<p><strong>Corpus example:</strong> <em>This is something which is XXX from XXX.</em></p>
<p>
  The pronoun <em>something</em> is vague, as it can refer to so many different
  items. Clarity in written English is determined by the specificity of the
  terminology selected. Indefinite pronouns such as <em>something</em>,
  <em>someone</em>, or <em>somewhere</em> limit their reference only to a type
  (thing, person, place) and are rather obscure.
</p>
<p>
  Items can be visualized on a cline from vague to specific:
  <br><em>thing &rsaquo; animal &rsaquo; mammal &rsaquo; dog &rsaquo; poodle &rsaquo; toy poodle</em>
</p>

<p class="mt-3">Click each corpus example to see the suggested revision.</p>
<div class="accordion mt-2" id="unit04-vague">
  {% call accordion("vague-a", "We understood the following things about a system...") %}
  <p><strong>Revision:</strong> <em>We understood the following <strong>aspects</strong> about a system...</em></p>
  <p><em>Aspects</em> is more specific than <em>things</em> and appropriate for describing properties of a system.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("vague-b", "Student point out something about the presentation...") %}
  <p><strong>Revision:</strong> <em>Students point out <strong>problems</strong> in the presentation...</em></p>
  <p>Replacing the vague pronoun with a specific noun clarifies what is being pointed out.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("vague-c", "When we want to buy something and estimate its price...") %}
  <p><strong>Revision:</strong> <em>When we want to buy a <strong>product</strong> and estimate its price...</em></p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("vague-d", "Looking at Table 4, four things can be seen.") %}
  <p><strong>Revision:</strong> <em>Looking at Table 4, four <strong>features</strong> can be seen.</em></p>
  {% endcall %}
</div>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 3 — Lexical ambiguity ══════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(3, "Lexical Ambiguity", "question-diamond") %}
<p><strong>Corpus example:</strong> <em>It is really high for XXX.</em></p>
<p>
  The adverb <em>really</em> has two possible specific meanings: either "to a high
  degree" (replaceable by <em>very</em>) or "in truth or fact" (replaceable by
  <em>actually</em>). In the original context it was not possible to determine the
  intended meaning — this is lexical ambiguity. Additionally, <em>really</em> is
  rather informal and fails to meet the genre expectations for formality.
</p>

<div class="mt-4">
{% call quizMC("quiz-04-a", "Which type of ambiguity arises when a single word has two possible meanings?", 1,
   "Lexical ambiguity occurs when a word has more than one meaning and the context does not make clear which meaning is intended. Referential ambiguity arises from pronouns; syntactic ambiguity from sentence structure.") %}
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-a" value="0"> Referential ambiguity</label>
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-a" value="1"> Lexical ambiguity</label>
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-a" value="2"> Syntactic ambiguity</label>
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-a" value="3"> Garden-path ambiguity</label>
{% endcall %}
</div>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 4 — Referential ambiguity ══════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(4, "Referential Ambiguity", "person-lines-fill") %}
<p><strong>Corpus example:</strong> <em>Referring to Smith [10], Jones notes that he...</em></p>
<p>
  The third-person pronoun <em>he</em> refers anaphorically to an earlier-mentioned
  person. However, there are two candidate antecedents (Smith and Jones), which
  creates confusion. This type of ambiguity also commonly occurs when pronouns
  such as <em>it</em> and <em>this</em> are used anaphorically.
</p>
<p>This ambiguity can be resolved by avoiding the pronoun entirely:</p>
<ul>
  <li><em>Jones notes that Smith [10]...</em></li>
  <li><em>Smith [10] notes that Jones...</em></li>
</ul>

<div class="mt-4">
{% call quizMC("quiz-04-b", "In 'Referring to Smith [10], Jones notes that he...', what causes the ambiguity?", 2,
   "The pronoun 'he' could refer to either Smith or Jones. This is referential ambiguity — the reader cannot determine which person the pronoun refers to without additional context. The solution is to replace the pronoun with the relevant proper name.") %}
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-b" value="0"> The word "referring" has two meanings</label>
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-b" value="1"> The citation number [10] is vague</label>
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-b" value="2"> The pronoun "he" could refer to either Smith or Jones</label>
  <label class="quiz-option"><input type="radio" name="quiz-04-b" value="3"> The sentence structure forces a wrong initial reading</label>
{% endcall %}
</div>
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 5 — Syntactic ambiguity ════════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(5, "Syntactic Ambiguity", "code-square") %}
<p><strong>Corpus example:</strong> <em>XXX found two AAA and one BBB, which CCC.</em></p>
<p>
  The relative clause <em>which CCC</em> may modify only <em>BBB</em>, or it could
  modify both <em>AAA</em> and <em>BBB</em>. This ambiguity arises from placing a
  modifier after noun phrases joined by a conjunction. Choose the revision that
  matches your intended meaning:
</p>

{% set syntaxTabs = [
  {id: "syn-one",  label: "Modifier applies to BBB only"},
  {id: "syn-all",  label: "Modifier applies to both"}
] %}
{% call tabSet("unit04-syntax", syntaxTabs) %}
  <div class="tab-pane fade show active" id="unit04-syntax-syn-one" role="tabpanel">
    <p>Move <em>BBB</em> to the start of the series so the modifier immediately follows it:</p>
    <p><em>XXX found <strong>one BBB, which CCC</strong>, and two AAA.</em></p>
  </div>
  <div class="tab-pane fade" id="unit04-syntax-syn-all" role="tabpanel">
    <p>Use a distributive determiner (<em>all of which</em>) to make the scope explicit:</p>
    <p><em>XXX found two AAA and one BBB, <strong>all of which</strong> CCC.</em></p>
  </div>
{% endcall %}
{% endcall %}


{# ══ Activity 6 — Garden-path sentences ═════════════════════════════ #}

{% call activitySection(6, "Garden-Path Sentences", "signpost-split") %}
<p><strong>Example:</strong> <em>The journal plans to publish your paper were just a rumour.</em></p>
<p>
  On reading this sentence, most readers will assume <em>plans</em> is a verb.
  On reaching the finite verb <em>were</em>, they must backtrack and re-read,
  re-categorizing <em>plans</em> as a noun. Garden-path sentences are not only
  ambiguous, but the initially assumed meaning is not the intended one.
</p>
<p>
  Garden-path sentences are difficult for writers to notice because the writer is
  primed to focus on the intended meaning. Second readers and proofreaders can,
  however, easily notice them because they need to backtrack to figure out the
  meaning. The challenge is not fixing them once found, but initially identifying them.
</p>

<div class="accordion mt-3" id="unit04-garden">
  {% call accordion("gp-a", "Read this sentence: 'The horse raced past the barn fell.' What is the intended meaning?") %}
  <p>The sentence means: <em>The horse <strong>that was</strong> raced past the barn fell.</em></p>
  <p>On first reading, most people parse "raced" as the main verb. Only on reaching "fell" does it become clear that "raced" is part of a reduced relative clause. This is a classic garden-path sentence.</p>
  {% endcall %}
  {% call accordion("gp-b", "How should garden-path sentences be revised?") %}
  <p>Disambiguation is usually straightforward once identified. Common strategies include:</p>
  <ul>
    <li>Adding a relative pronoun: <em>The horse <strong>that was</strong> raced past the barn fell.</em></li>
    <li>Reordering the sentence to avoid the ambiguous parse</li>
    <li>Replacing a noun that can also function as a verb with a clearer noun</li>
  </ul>
  {% endcall %}
</div>
{% endcall %}


